    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-15T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-15T12:00:00-05:00" n="834"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d834">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/13235: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-15T19:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 15, 1941—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 16—8:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>300. First British troops consisting of an Australian battalion entered Beirut
                    about 1:00 p.m. today. At the request of the Colonel I took him to call on
                    Admiral Gouton—see my 286, July 10, 11 a.m.—and assisted him and his political
                    officer in establishing contacts with the heads of certain administrations
                    charged with the maintenance of order, food control, et cetera. The attitude of
                    the French official was correct, courteous and helpful.</p>
                <p>General Wilson and General Catroux arrive tomorrow morning.</p>
                <p>As previously reported by me, neither Admiral Gouton nor any other French
                    official is permitted by Vichy to have any relations with the Free French
                    authorities who are about to take over in Beirut. This will, of course,
                    complicate the situation enormously and it will require the utmost tact on the
                    part of everybody to avoid an impasse at the very outset.</p>
                <p>Repeated to London and Vichy.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
